{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525629"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:16:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14088"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14088"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.19,0.41,0.34,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52700"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6756"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38059"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2890"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14705"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52700"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about a rash on her hands that has been present for three months. She reports no itching or pain associated with the rash. She has also noticed that she becomes overheated easily and has had several episodes of diarrhoea recently. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She purchased new laundry detergent last week and had just moved to a new crowded rental apartment. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Inspection of her hands reveals multiple flesh-colored to slightly erythematous papules arranged in a ring-like pattern on the dorsum of both hands (Image). The lesions are approximately 2-3 cm in diameter.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Psoriasis","Erythema multiforme","Tinea corporis","Granuloma annulare","Sarcoidosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Egranuloma annulare\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition typically presents as asymptomatic, flesh-colored or slightly erythematous papules arranged in a ring-like or annular pattern after a trigger such as trauma or bite . The dorsum of the hands is a common location, and the absence of symptoms (such as no itching or pain) is characteristic. It is more common in young people or in older adults over 50 years of age, and typically occurs on females. In younger people it tends to present as smooth red papules over joints, hands or elbows. Adults more frequently demonstrate as multiple pink or skin-coloured small mildly itchy papules over skin folds and may be associated with HIV, diabetes mellitus or malignancy. Localised granuloma annulare can also be associated with autoimmune thyroiditis which is hinted at in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGranuloma annulare is often self-limiting and usually resolve without treatment within a few months to two years. If treatment is desired, topical corticosteroids are typically the first-line approach for localised disease. For widespread or resistant cases, systemic treatments such as phototherapy or oral medications may be considered. A skin biopsy can confirm the diagnosis if there is uncertainty, but the clinical presentation is often sufficient for diagnosis in typical cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETinea corporis\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as ringworm, can present with annular lesions but typically has a scaly, erythematous border and may be pruritic. The lack of scaling and symptoms makes this diagnosis less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E on the hands usually presents with well-demarcated, erythematous plaques with silvery scale which are not seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with cutaneous manifestations, but these are typically firm, reddish-brown papules or nodules, often on the face or extremities. The annular arrangement seen in this patient is not typical of sarcoidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema multiforme\u003C/strong\u003E presents with target-like lesions that have a central dusky area surrounded by pale and erythematous rings. It is often associated with preceding infections or medications and can be accompanied by systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Granuloma annulare typically presents as asymptomatic, flesh-colored or erythematous papules arranged in a ring-like pattern.","Granuloma annulare is often self-limiting and may resolve without treatment within two years."],"references":["Oakley A. Granuloma annulare. In: DermnetNZ [online].  2020. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/granuloma-annulare","Minocha R, Kurien A. Granuloma Annulare.  In: The Australasian College of Dermatologists [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/granuloma-annulare-2/","Joshi TP, Duvic M. Granuloma Annulare: An Updated Review of Epidemiology, Pathogenesis, and Treatment Options. Am J Clin Dermatol. 2022 Jan;23(1):37-50. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8423598/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38059"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14088"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20979"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20979"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hPUh9BmDfEoQbKjbdMoctEI2fvdITy.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hPUh9BmDfEoQbKjbdMoctEI2fvdITy.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38059"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-09T11:53:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-09T12:11:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6756"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52700"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rela